{"cursor":"13511","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Unspoken rules' are behavioral constraints imposed in organizations or\nsocieties that are not voiced or written down. They usually exist in unspoken\nand unwritten format because they form a part of the logical argument or course\nof action implied by tacit assumptions. Examples involving unspoken rules\ninclude unwritten and unofficial organizational hierarchies, organizational\nculture, and acceptable behavioral norms governing interactions between\norganizational members.\n\nFor example, the captain of a ship is always expected to be the last to evacuate\nit in a disaster. Or, as Vince Waldron wrote, \"A pet, once named, instantly\nbecomes an inseparable member of the family.\" Vince Waldron,\n[http://books.google.gr/books?id=BCTj8iffkKAC&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq= The\nOfficial Dick Van Dyke Show Book], Hal Leonard, 2001, p. 151.\n","linknr":255,"url":"Unspoken_rule","recorded":1362892752,"links":26,"instances":["nautical"],"pdf":["http://lpfi.org/docs/HOWFAIRReport.pdf","http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom-UnitedStates/Local%20Assets/Documents/us_consulting_EnterpriseRiskIntelligence_010512.pdf","http://www.avocetchange.ca/tools-resources/organization-effectiveness.pdf","http://shura.shu.ac.uk/3981/1/Paper_preprint.pdf","http://www.thesystemsthinker.com/contest/PDFs/1403pk.pdf","http://shura.shu.ac.uk/4035/1/Organisational_Memetics.pdf","http://www.dft.gov.uk/mca/rp521_final_report-4.pdf","http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom-UnitedStates/Local%20Assets/Documents/IMOs/Governance%20and%20Risk%20Management/us_risk_ThePeopleSideofRiskIntelligence.pdf","http://www.adlittle.com/downloads/tx_adlprism/Prism_2006_s2_3_history.pdf","http://www.adlittle.com/downloads/tx_adlprism/1998_q2_17-21.pdf","http://www.adlittle.com/downloads/tx_adlprism/1994_q2_12-19.pdf","http://www.adlittle.com/downloads/tx_adlprism/1993_q4_06-10.pdf"],"categories":["Logic","Rules"],"headings":["Employment and discrimination","The